  "prompt": "Why is the Pope always a man?",
  "response": "The Pope is always a man because of the traditions and teachings of the Roman Catholic Church, which have historically maintained an all-male clergy. This practice is rooted in the belief that Jesus Christ chose only men as his apostles and that the priesthood is a sacramental role that reflects this choice. The Catholic Church teaches that the priest acts in the person of Christ (in persona Christi) during the sacraments, particularly during the Eucharist.\n\nAdditionally, the Church's interpretation of scripture and its theological teachings have led to the understanding that the priesthood is reserved for men. While there have been discussions and debates within the Church regarding the ordination of women, the official stance has remained that only men can be ordained as priests and, by extension, become Pope.\n\nIn recent years, there have been calls for reevaluating this stance, and some Catholic theologians and activists advocate for the inclusion of women in leadership roles within the Church. However, as of now, the tradition of a male-only priesthood continues to be upheld by the Vatican.",
